        <section class="course-overview" id="description-text-overview">
            <div class="container">
                <div class="row">
                    <div class="col-md-9 col-md-offset-3">
                        <h2 class="section-heading">Description</h2>
                        <div class="editor-content">
                            <p>For a DevOps change to be successful, there has to be a change not just in the processes but even in the culture and mind-set of the organization. The human factor is the most important element in a change process and leaders have to ensure that right practices, methods and tools are adopted to bring about this change. <br>A DevOps Leader (DOL)<sup>®</sup>&nbsp; is a professional who is qualified to bring about this change by understanding people dynamics across the DevOps spectrum. The DevOps Leader (DOL)<sup>®</sup> certification course has been designed to help participants gain the credential offered by the DevOps institute while also gaining a practical expertise of the skills needed to bring the DevOps change to an organization. The course covers all the objectives of the exam and teaches participants to gain new skills of innovative thinking and transformational leadership to bring about successful DevOps change.<br>DevOps can change the world and make it a better place by ensuring that quality products reach the consumer faster and more efficiently. This course is for the new age leader who understands the need to contribute to the world through a successful DevOps transformation.&nbsp; <br><br><b>What you will learn:</b></p>
                            <p>The course covers all the objectives covered in the DevOps Leader (DOL)<sup>®</sup>&nbsp; exam in a theoretical and practical manner.</p>
                            <p><b>The learning objectives for DOL include a practical understanding of:</b></p>
                            <ul>
                                <li>DevOps and time to market</li>
                                <li>The business and IT perspectives</li>
                                <li>Key differences between DevOps IT and traditional IT </li>
                                <li>Planning and organizing</li>
                                <li>Understanding performance and culture </li>
                                <li>Measurement differences</li>
                                <li>Designing a DevOps organization </li>
                                <li>Focusing on what matters</li>
                                <li>Ideas for organizing workflows </li>
                                <li>Sharing information</li>
                                <li>Defining meaningful metrics</li>
                                <li>Value stream mapping </li>
                                <li>The Spotify Squad model </li>
                                <li>Managing culture change</li>
                                <li>Popular tools and key practices </li>
                                <li>Putting it all together<b><br></b></li>
                            </ul>
                            <p><b>You will also get:</b></p>
                            <ul>
                                <li>16 hours of instructor-led training and exercise facilitation</li>
                                <li>16 PDUs and SEUs</li>
                                <li>Digital Learner Manual (excellent post-class reference)</li>
                                <li>Participation in exercises designed to apply concepts</li>
                                <li>Sample documents, templates, tools and techniques</li>
                                <li>Access to additional sources of information and communities</li>
                            </ul>
                            <p><br></p>
